are only few contemporary witnesses left who can provide information about the conditions in the former camps of Nazi tyranny. The archived material is often unproductive - particularly that of smaller facilities, such as the field camps and labor camps. Yet their traces are scattered all over Central Europe. What do these material remains have to tell? Archaeology has hardly been used yet as a tool that can help to explore this question. Reinhard Bernbeck takes archaeological findings found under the Tempelhof Airfield in Berlin as an example to show in detail what this "archaeology of contemporary history" can do, where it has its limitations and how it fits into a controversial "culture of remembering".  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zGermanyzBerlin. 0aMaterial culturezGermanyzBerlin. 0aMaterial culturezGermany. 0aMaterial culture. 0aNational socialism and archaeologyzGermanyzBerlin. 0aNational socialismzGermanyzBerlin. 4aArchäologie. 4aAusgrabungen. 4aDrittes Reich. 4aGeschichtswissenschaft. 4aKZ. 4aKultur. 4aKulturgeschichte. 4aKulturtheorie. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aMaterielle Kultur. 4aModerne. 4aNS-Lager. 4aNS-Terror. 4aTempelhof. 4aZeitgeschichte. 4aZwangsarbeitslager. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aArchaeology.  aContemporary History.  aCultural History.  aCultural Studies.  aCultural Theory.  aCulture.  aHistory.  aMaterial Culture.  aModernity.  aThird Reich.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2017z9783110547764oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839439678zCo-access D